I have all the data. Here's the full performance analysis:

---

## .NET Performance Scan тАФ `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`

**Context:** Hot path тАФ millions of log entries/minute (user-confirmed).

### Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|--------|------|
| `.IndexOf(string)` no StringComparison | 0 |
| `.Substring(` | 0 |
| `.StartsWith/.EndsWith` no StringComparison | 0 |
| `.ToLowerInvariant()` | 1 |
| Chained `.Replace(` | 0 |
| `params` declarations | 1 |
| `.Trim()` | 1 |
| LINQ `.Select/.Where/.Take/.Aggregate` | 12 |
| LINQ `.Any` | 1 |
| `.ToList()` | 1 |
| `.ToArray()` | 1 |
| Unsealed classes | 1 of 1 (0 sealed) |
| `new Regex(` / `string.Format` | 0 |

### Findings

---

#### 1. LINQ chains on hot path (15 call sites) 
ЁЯФ┤ **Critical**

**Impact:** Every `Humanize()` call allocates multiple enumerator objects + delegate instances. At millions of calls/minute, this creates extreme GC pressure.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`: L128, L140, L143, L146, L149, L158, L169, L244, L261тАУ262, L270тАУ272, L284, L304

**Fix:** Replace LINQ chains with `foreach` loops and direct array/list indexing. Examples:

`IsContainingOnlyNullValue` (L127тАУ128):
```csharp
// Before:  !timeParts.Any(x => x != null)
// After:
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(List<string?> timeParts)
{
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
        if (part != null) return false;
    return true;
}
```

`SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan` (L133тАУ150) тАФ 3 chained LINQ operators тЖТ single foreach:
```csharp
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    var result = new List<string?>(precision);
    int count = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
    {
        if (count >= precision) break;
        if (countEmptyUnits) { count++; if (part != null) result.Add(part); }
        else { if (part != null) { result.Add(part); count++; } }
    }
    return result;
}
```

`ConcatenateTimeSpanParts` (L155тАУ171) тАФ `.Where().ToList()` + `.Take()`:
```csharp
private static string ConcatenateTimeSpanParts(
    List<string?> timeSpanParts, CultureInfo culture, string collectionSeparator)
{
    var parts = new List<string>(timeSpanParts.Count);
    foreach (var p in timeSpanParts)
        if (p != null) parts.Add(p);
    // ... rest uses parts directly with indexer
}
```

`HumanizeDisplayStrings` (L266тАУ286) тАФ `.Select().Where().ToArray()` chain:
```csharp
var items = new List<string>(strings is ICollection<string?> c ? c.Count : 4);
foreach (var item in strings)
{
    if (item == null) continue;
    var trimmed = item.Trim();
    if (!string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(trimmed)) items.Add(trimmed);
}
```

---

#### 2. Enum.ToString() + .ToLowerInvariant() per call тАФ compound 3 allocations (1 site)
ЁЯФ┤ **Critical**

**Impact:** `FormatTimePart` (L174тАУ177) calls `unit.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()` тЖТ enum reflection + lowercase string + interpolated string = **3 heap allocations per time part**, called for every non-zero unit in every log entry.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`: L175тАУ176

**Fix:** Cache unit names in a static array indexed by enum value:
```csharp
private static readonly string[] s_unitNames =
    ["year", "month", "week", "day", "hour", "minute", "second", "millisecond"];

private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    var unitName = s_unitNames[(int)unit];
    return value == 1 ? $"{value} {unitName}" : $"{value} {unitName}s";
}
```

---

#### 3. `params IStringTransformer[]` array allocation (1 instance)
ЁЯЯб **Moderate**

**Impact:** Every `Transform()` call allocates a `T[]` for the params array тАФ even single-transformer calls (the most common case).

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`: L303

**Fix:** Add a 1-arg overload for the common single-transformer case:
```csharp
public static string Transform(
    this string input, CultureInfo culture, IStringTransformer transformer) =>
    transformer.Transform(input);
```

---

#### 4. Unsealed `DefaultCollectionFormatter` (1 of 1 classes; 0 sealed)
тД╣я╕П **Info**

**Impact:** JIT cannot devirtualize `virtual` method calls. No subclasses found in this file.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`: L208

**Fix:** Add `sealed` keyword if no external subclasses exist.

**Caveat:** The class has `virtual` methods, suggesting intentional extensibility. Only seal if no subclasses exist anywhere in the codebase.

---

#### 5. Static initializer uses `Enumerable.Reverse` (1 instance)
тД╣я╕П **Info**

**Impact:** One-time allocation at class load тАФ not per-call. Trivially replaceable.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`: L41

**Fix:** Replace with a reversed array literal:
```csharp
private static readonly TimeUnit[] TimeUnits =
    [TimeUnit.Millisecond, TimeUnit.Second, TimeUnit.Minute,
     TimeUnit.Hour, TimeUnit.Day, TimeUnit.Week, TimeUnit.Month, TimeUnit.Year];
```

---

### Positive Patterns

- тЬЕ No sync-over-async тАФ no `Task.Result` or `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()`
- тЬЕ String interpolation used instead of `string.Format` (L170, L176, L285)
- тЬЕ `List<string?>` pre-sized with capacity 8 (L91)
- тЬЕ No Regex, HttpClient, or JSON serialization concerns

---

### Summary

| Severity | Count | Top Issue |
|----------|-------|-----------|
| ЁЯФ┤ Critical | 2 | LINQ chains creating 5-8 allocations per Humanize() call; Enum.ToString() compound allocations |
| ЁЯЯб Moderate | 1 | `params` array allocation on every Transform() call |
| тД╣я╕П Info | 2 | Unsealed class; one-time Enumerable.Reverse |

